The paper deals with the problem of cake-cutting, which is a classic problem in computational social choice. The focus is on single-peaked preferences, which is a well-studied preference domain in computational social choice. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.GT (Computational Social Choice and Game Theory). The paper also proposes alternative mechanisms to achieve Pareto optimality and envy-freeness, which suggests that it could be relevant to the categories cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also involves the study of welfare losses, which could be relevant to the category cs.EC (Economics and Computation). Finally, the paper involves the characterization of Pareto optimal allocations, which could be relevant to the category cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
